ism had unintended consequences, because the liberal immigration policies they supported helped to end over three centuries of white Protestant dominance in American society.Yet, Pruitt argues, in losing their cultural supremacy, mainline Protestants were able to reassess their mission. They rolled back more strident forms of xenophobia, substantively altering the face of mainline Protestantism and laying foundations for their responses to today’s immigration debates. More than just a historical portrait, this volume is a timely reminder of the power of religious influence in political matters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aEmigration and immigrationxReligious aspectsxProtestant churchesxHistoryy20th century. 0aProtestant churchesxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / Religious Intolerance, Persecution & Conflict.2bisacsh  aAmericanization.  aAsian exclusion.  aBraceros.  aChurch World Service.  aCold War.  aGreat Depression.  aImmigration Act of 1924.  aImmigration Act of 1965.  aJapanese immigrants.  aJapanese internment.  aJewish refugees.  aMcCarran-Walter Act.  aSecond Red Scare.  aWorld War II.  acultural pluralism.  agender.  ahome missions.  aimmigration policy.  aimmigration.  anativism.  arace.  arefugee resettlement.  arefugees.  areligious pluralism.  asocial gospel.  atwentieth century.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479803576.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479803576423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479803576/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles